OREON Hot Strip Rolling Mill Maintenance Manual

The hot strip rolling mill reduces thick steel slabs into thin coils at high temperatures (1100 C). The mill stand utilizes work rolls, backup rolls, hydraulic roll-gap cylinder actuators, and heavy-duty spindle couplings driven by the main motor through the reduction gearbox.

Common failure modes: roll surface degradation (spalling, fire cracking, or thermal wear) causing surface defects on the steel strip; hydraulic cylinder seal failure causing roll gap control instability and strip thickness variation; roll neck bearing overheating from lubrication starvation or cooling water contamination; and spindle coupling misalignment causing high torque vibrations.

Corrective actions: inspect rolls with ultrasonic testing during roll changes; replace rolls on schedule or immediately upon surface defect detection; inspect hydraulic cylinders for bypass leakage and replace rod seals; verify roll cooling spray nozzles are unclogged and operating at 6.0 bar; and verify automatic roll-gap leveling calibration before each rolling campaign.

Roll-Gap Lubrication: roll neck bearings use mist lubrication. Continuous oil flow and air pressure must be verified. High temperature (above 85 C) indicates bearing wear or cooling water ingress.
